               <p>SECOND COUNT, stating it to be fixed to a building of his.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-190-person1900">
                  ROBERT 
                  CLAYARDS
               <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1900" type="surname" value="CLAYARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1900" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1900" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in <placeName id="t18210912-190-crimeloc1115">Crown-street, St. Giles's</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18210912-190-crimeloc1115" type="placeName" value="Crown-street, St. Giles's"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18210912-190-crimeloc1115" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210912-190-off1113 t18210912-190-crimeloc1115"></join>, next door but one to Mr. M'Donough. I keep pigeons on my roof. On the 28th of July, about nine o'clock in the morning, I was on the roof attending to them, and saw the prisoner on M'Donough's roof (he lodged next door), in the act of cutting the lead from the loft door; I walked across the next house, and stood by the chimney; he cut it away, brought it to the gutter, and was in the act of cutting it into smaller pieces when he saw me. I said. "You have no right to this, I will take it." I took it down into my own house and gave it to the officer, and told M'Donough, he sent for an officer who took him. I let him go down through his own house.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. ADOLPHUS. Q. Were you on the roof before him - A. No, he was just beginning when I went up; he is a <rs id="t18210912-190-deflabel1116" type="occupation">bricklayer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210912-190-defend1898 t18210912-190-deflabel1116"></join>, he came to me before the officer came, and said he was sorry for what he had done; the officer came in half an hour, he remained at home.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-190-person1901">
                  MICHAEL 
                  M'DONOUGH
               <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1901" type="surname" value="M'DONOUGH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1901" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-190-person1901" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live next door but one to Clayard's, and am a <rs id="t18210912-190-viclabel1117" type="occupation">carver and gilder</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210912-190-victim1899 t18210912-190-viclabel1117"></join>. I sent Lewis to match the lead on the trap door - it fitted.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Are you a housekeeper - A. Yes; it is in St. Giles's parish. I find the prisoner was an industrious man, has a large family, and was in distress,</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-190-person1902">
                  LEWIS 
                  LEWIS
